    "summary": "As a consultant I assist the Pallas project on System engineering, project mangement, and requirements\n\n I am also working on Requirements Assistant as a unique tool that analyzes requirements in a natural language.\nhttp://www.requirementsassistant.nl\n\n\nAs a consultant I read,  see, and review many specifications for new (sub)-systems. They come from ASML, Volvo trucks, Philips Medical, Pallas nuclear reactor,Dutch Railways (NS), Amsterdam metro system, Thales, European Central Bank (ECB),  etc.  Indeed, a wide variety of domains. Apart from giving them a thorough review they also serve as inspiration for \u201cRequirements Assistant\u201d. This tool is the home of many rules, that find errors in specifications. Over the past 20 years it is a growing body of knowledge aimed to find potential trouble in development specifications. These rules focus on completeness, consistency, vagueness, testability, and all the other desirable attributes of a specification. And , this analysis also works for a set of specifications.\n\nA recent example: I received a development specification of about 50 pages for a hi-tech product. The document was reviewed by 60 people, some of them domain experts and system engineers. Not just once, but the specification was reviewed three times, then approved, and put under change control.\n\nThen a review with Requirements Assistant was executed, and it found 30 major issues. So, if you see the benefit of  this timely discovery of trouble as a way to reduce product development time, and product design cost, then join! The discussion of issues is also an interesting possibility to close the loop with the design people. Common understanding of requirements!\n\nSpecialties: Requirements analysis, system engineering, program management\n",
